    "raw": "Speculative design outline\n\nGoal\n- Give agents a compact Python-like language for loops, aggregation, parsing, and calculation without granting ambient Python authority.\n- Keep ordinary computation broadly unconstrained while making every externally observable effect explicit and policy-controlled.\n\nCandidate architecture\n- Parse a deliberately small Python subset into an AST; reject unsupported syntax before execution.\n- Evaluate in a purpose-built interpreter or tightly controlled runtime with no ambient imports, reflection, dynamic code loading, object internals, or implicit filesystem/network/process access.\n- Provide pure built-ins and bounded standard data types for arithmetic, strings, bytes, collections, iteration, comprehensions, functions, and structured data.\n- Represent effects as typed capabilities (for example read_file, write_file, fetch_url, run_command, clock, environment) rather than exposing Python libraries directly.\n- Route capability requests through the agent host so the existing permission model can allow, deny, or ask the user; return structured results to the script.\n- Constrain executable invocation with an allowlist or policy descriptors covering binary identity, arguments, cwd, environment, stdin/stdout, timeout, and output limits.\n\nSafety boundaries to explore\n- Separate authority restriction from resource control: capability mediation limits effects, while quotas cover CPU, memory, recursion, generated output, and nontermination.\n- Ensure values returned by capabilities cannot become confused-deputy handles or smuggle unrestricted host objects into the evaluator.\n- Define deterministic behavior where practical, with explicit opt-in access to time, randomness, and environment state.\n- Log each effect request and decision for auditability and replay.\n- Treat native extensions, pickle/marshal, eval/exec, import hooks, descriptors, dunder traversal, and arbitrary exception/object introspection as out of scope.\n\nDesign alternatives\n- Custom Python-subset interpreter: strongest semantic control, highest implementation cost.\n- Compile validated AST to Python plus OS sandbox: faster prototype, but AST validation alone is not a security boundary.\n- Existing restricted language or WASM guest with Pythonic syntax/front-end: stronger isolation, potentially poorer agent ergonomics.\n- Out-of-process worker with RPC capabilities: likely baseline even with a custom interpreter, providing defense in depth.\n\nOpen questions\n- Which Python constructs are essential for agent-generated scripts, and which can be omitted?\n- Are filesystem reads effects requiring permission, or can the host pre-mount an approved snapshot?\n- Should repeated equivalent effects be approved once, per loop, or via a scoped lease?\n- How are package-like helpers curated and versioned without reopening imports?\n- What result and diagnostic format best lets an agent recover from denied capabilities or quota exhaustion?\n\nPrototype path\n1. Specify syntax, value model, and capability protocol with examples.\n2. Threat-model escapes, confused-deputy paths, denial of service, and policy bypass.\n3. Build a minimal parser/evaluator supporting pure loops and calculations.\n4. Add one mediated read capability and one constrained process capability through a mock permission broker.\n5. Test denial, approval caching, quotas, determinism, audit logs, and known Python sandbox-escape patterns.\n6. Compare usability and isolation against an out-of-process CPython prototype and a WASM-based guest."
  },
